<font color="#FF0000">LANGUAGE AND VIETNAM TEACHING</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb 22 22:08:46 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all the guys:<br>
    In regards to the comments on the war, I can see your point and agree.  War is dirty, nasty and cruel.  My point about language at this point has nothing to do with this.  I'm a school teacher and a Nam Vet.  I teach and write curriculum for intermediate and junior high.  I just question the use of foul language-you know curse words.  Among adults and vets fine, I can't think of any other words to describe some things that happened other than curses.  In teaching, I have to present the essence of Vietnam (tough for those who didn't experience to understand-I was there and am not sure I understand it all).  I CAN'T use curses and I feel that it can be done without them as many fellow vet guest speakers have proven.  Also, many parents would object to the bad language as some sometimes are concerned about the content of lessons on war.  What I meant had absolutly nothing to do about the language of war among these discussions, it had to do with teaching, the classroom, and children.  So, from now on you don't have to try to convince me of anything.  War is not clean and neat, but school HAS TO BE!!
<p><code>--   (Joe) </code><p>


